\begin_layout Section
Preliminaries
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Lambda Field Representation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using Octomaps for the path planning and navigation for each agent in the fleet.
 Utilise the basics of lambda field to work out the traversability risks of voxel based on how likely the robot loses all kinetic energy (stops moving).
 The risks can be calculated for each discretised voxel cell based off the OctoMap information stored at each voxel such as temperature,
 radiation and wind.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
First consider a 2D case,
 for a positive scalar field 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda(x)$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

the probability to encounter at least one break down in a path 
\begin_inset Formula $P\subset\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
p(break|P)=1-exp(-\intop_{P}\lambda(x)dx)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is impossible to both compute and store a field 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda(x)$
\end_inset

.
 Hence the field must be discretised similar to a Bayesian occupancy grid.
 Given the cells are small enough,
 a path P crossing cells in the array 
\begin_inset Formula $C=\{c_{0},\ldots,c_{N}\}$
\end_inset

,
 where each cell has an area of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and is associated by a calculated 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{i}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
p(break|P)\approx1-exp(-\Lambda(C)),
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Lambda(C)=A\sum_{c_{i}\in C}\lambda_{i}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now extend the scalar 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 field to account for multi-modal risk influences by defining risk contributions from various environmental sources,
 such as thermal gradients,
 radiation exposure,
 and wind shear.
 These are denoted respectively as 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{T}(x,y,z),\lambda_{R}(x,y,z),\lambda_{W}(x,y,z)$
\end_inset

 and they represent spatially varying risk intensities extracted from OctoMap voxel metadata.
 To aggregate these into a unified risk score per voxel,
 a linear combination is used with weights 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{T},\omega_{R},\omega_{W}$
\end_inset

 that can be adapted to reflect the sensitivity of different robot platforms to specific environmental stressors.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To manage risk at a resolution suitable for high-level planning,
 the lambda field is aggregated over discrete voxel chunks.
 These chunks represent local spatial regions in the environment,
 allowing the system to reduce computational complexity while preserving localised risk characteristics.
 The expected lambda value 
\begin_inset Formula $E[\Lambda_{c}]$
\end_inset

 within a chunk provides a summary statistic that captures the average traversability risk across all constituent voxels.
 This aggregation is formalised as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
E[\Lambda_{c}]=\frac{1}{N}\sum_{x,y,z\in C(i,j,k)}\Lambda(x,y,z)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda(x,y,z)$
\end_inset

 lambda field value at each voxel.
 This results in a per-voxel composite risk field 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Lambda_{C}(i,j,k)=\frac{1}{N}\sum_{x,y,z\in C(i,j,k)}(\lambda_{T}(x,y,z)+\lambda_{R}(x,y,z)+\lambda_{W}(x,y,z).
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Including platform-specific variable weights for different robots the form of the equation becomes
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Lambda_{C}(i,j,k)=\frac{1}{N}\sum_{x,y,z\in C(i,j,k)}(\omega_{T}\lambda_{T}(x,y,z)+\omega_{R}\lambda_{R}(x,y,z)+\omega_{W}\lambda_{W}(x,y,z).
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This equation computes the average weighted risk within a volumetric chunk 
\begin_inset Formula $C(i,j,k)$
\end_inset

 comprising of 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 voxels.
 This equation computes the average weighted risk within a volumetric chunk of 
\begin_inset Formula $H^{3}$
\end_inset

 voxels;
 
\begin_inset Formula $H=16$
\end_inset

 is chosen to balance computational efficiency with local resolution,
 enabling localised risk assessment suitable for path planning and task allocation.
 The expected lambda risk value 
\begin_inset Formula $E[\Lambda_{c}]$
\end_inset

 from Equation (8),
 is now placed into the probability of agent break down in Equation (6) to assess the mission-loss metric of that agent compared to alternative robots.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Importantly,
 the weighting parameters 
\begin_inset Formula $𝜔$
\end_inset

 are platform-specific and must be calibrated empirically or via simulation to reflect operational tolerances;
 for instance,
 aerial drones may assign higher weight to wind-based risk,
 while ground vehicles may prioritise temperature or terrain instability.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This 3D lambda field formulation enables a robot to estimate the probability of kinetic failure (i.e.,
 motion loss or stoppage) over a continuous or discretised path through the environment.
 Integrated into the planning pipeline,
 this model supports risk-aware decision-making by penalising trajectories through high-risk regions and promoting paths that optimize mission reliability.
 Furthermore,
 its modular structure allows additional risk layers (e.g.,
 chemical exposure or structural load) to be incorporated in future extensions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Efficiency-Based Risk Representation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
While physical terrain-based hazards are central to estimating immediate locomotion failure,
 long-term mission success in multi-robot deployments also hinges on internal system constraints.
 These include energy depletion,
 computational strain,
 communication reliability,
 and sensor degradation.
 Unlike spatial traversability risks,
 these efficiency-based risks often emerge from the robot's internal state but may also be influenced by environmental context.
 To support robust planning and resource-aware coordination,
 this section extends the lambda field formulation to incorporate such efficiency-based risks into the overall physical spatial risk model.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Voxel-Integrated Efficiency Risk Fields
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Some efficiency-related risks such as battery and communication risks can exhibit spatial dependence and are thus representable within the voxel-based lambda field framework.
 For example,
 terrain features influence energy expenditure,
 while environmental occlusion can degrade signal strength.
 We define two such fields:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Battery Risk Field 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{B}(x,y,z)$
\end_inset

:
 Represents increased likelihood of failure due to high energy consumption over specific terrain types.
 A general formulation:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\lambda_{B}(x,y,z)=\Upsilon_{1}\centerdot slope(x,y,z)+\Upsilon_{2}\centerdot surface(x,y,z)+\Upsilon_{3}\centerdot elevation(x,y,z),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the weights 
\begin_inset Formula $\Upsilon_{i}$
\end_inset

 are learned or tuned variables per robot platform that reflect sensitivity to terrain-induced energy cost.
 Such as the slope angle of the terrain,
 the surface roughness and elevation gain.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Communication Risk Field
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{C}(x,y,z)$
\end_inset

:
 Quantifies the likelihood of signal dropout at a given location.
 One empirical approximation is:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\lambda_{C}(x,y,z)=1-\frac{S(x,y,z)}{S_{Max}},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $S(x,y,z)$
\end_inset

 is the predicted or observed signal strength and 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{Max}$
\end_inset

 is the maximum measurable signal level.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These voxel-level risks are incorporated into the global risk aggregation model alongside physical risks (e.g.,
 thermal,
 radiation,
 wind) as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Lambda_{C}(i,j,k)=\frac{1}{N}\sum_{x,y,z\in C(i,j,k)}(\sum_{r\in R}\omega_{r}\lambda_{r}(x,y,z)).
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $R=\{T,R,W,B,C...\}$
\end_inset

 denotes the full set of environmental and efficiency risks.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Agent-Centric Efficiency Risk Model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Other efficiency risks are non-spatial in nature and tied directly to the agent’s onboard state,
 such as processor load or sensor degradation.
 These cannot be represented spatially but can be incorporated as agent-level scalar terms.
 We define an aggregate efficiency risk score for each unique agent (
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

):
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Lambda_{eff}^{(i)}=\omega_{B}\centerdot\lambda_{B}+\omega_{C}\centerdot\lambda_{C}+\omega_{S}\centerdot\lambda_{S}+\omega_{N}\centerdot\lambda_{N}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Where:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{B}$
\end_inset

:
 Battery depletion rate (e.g.,
 power draw over time),
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{C}$
\end_inset

:
 Computational load (e.g.,
 processor usage),
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{S}$
\end_inset

:
 Sensor degradation (e.g.,
 reduced accuracy or dropout rate),
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{N}$
\end_inset

:
 Network strain (e.g.,
 bandwidth limits,
 packet loss),
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

:
 Weights reflecting robot-specific tolerances.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These parameters are dynamically updated based on onboard telemetry and health diagnostics.
 For example,
 a high 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{S}$
\end_inset

 may result from temperature-induced sensor noise,
 while 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{C}$
\end_inset

 could reflect real-time CPU utilization.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Hybrid Risk Integration for Decision-Making
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To support coherent task planning,
 the total risk for a given robot trajectory is computed by fusing physical spatial risk values at each voxel (
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda_{spatial}(x,y,z)=(\sum_{r\in R}\omega_{r}\lambda_{r}(x,y,z))$
\end_inset

) seen from equation (13) and agent-centric risks:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Lambda_{total}=\Lambda_{spatial}(x,y,z)+\Lambda_{eff}^{(i)}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This hybrid formulation enables the planner to reason not just about the geometric and environmental cost of a path,
 but also about the internal state of the executing agent.
 For instance,
 a terrain segment may be geometrically navigable,
 but if an agent’s battery or computational load is critical,
 that path is penalised or avoided when the 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda_{total}$
\end_inset

is calculated in equation (6).
\end_layout

