\begin_layout Section
Demonstrations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Following the final goal of this project,
 it is important to deploy the robot fleet in live real-world demonstrations to prove the framework can work outside of a simulation.
 When dealing with a fleet of heterogeneous locomotion-diverse robots there are many sub-systems that go into a deployment for a real-world mission;
 thus it is correct practice to individually test each sub-system into the fleet through experiments to evaluate the problems at each stage integration and validate performance.
 Therefore,
 this work undertook a robotic fleet demonstration to inspect the serial communication between robotic agents within a centralised fleet.
 Communication is the primary method of coordination for the agents inside the fleet during SAR mission and without it they would unable to relay OctoMap information,
 traversability metrics and task allocation.
 In the demonstration three autonomous agents were deployed into an open world airbase in Wales;
 Two quadrotor drones and one rover were deployed with autonomous navigation.
 The goal of the experiment was to achieve GPS tracking between agents,
 such that each robot could pass it's own GPS coordinates through a ground station to the rest of the fleet and to converge the robots into a convoy essentially following the longitude and latitude coordinates of the agent vertically above it.
 The altitude of the drones were set at 40 metres and 20 metres to avoid mid-air collisions,
 while the rover was on the ground floor (0 metres).
 Altitude was set amongst all robots and altitude control was ignored.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Experimental Setup
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The robots were fabricated with components that enable the open source autopilot system,
 ArduPilot,
 which utilises MAVLink Protocols and the Mission Planner GSC.
 Each robot in the fleet had a flight controller (for the ArduPilot firmware),
 a compass (for GPS),
 an inertial measurement unit (IMU),
 a radio transmitter and receiver (to enable manual control with a hand held transmitter) and a Wi-Fi transmitter/receiver (for autonomous mission planning).
 The aerial quadrotors also carried altitude sensors,
 while the rover was installed with a Real Time Kinematic (RTK) unit to enhance the accuracy of positioning data from GPS as it was subjected to large force harmonics when driving across rough terrain.
\end_layout

